@startuml
title Creature Control System (a.k.a. Dungeon Master) Class Diagram

class Creature {
  + ai_type : creature_ai_ref
}

class Level_master {
  + update(vector<player_input>* inputs)
  - move_creatures(vector<player_input>* inputs)
  - resolve_combat(Creature* attacker, Creature* defender)
  - interact(Creature* creature, Interactable* tgt)
}

class Level_map {
  - tiles : matrix<2, Tile*>
  - creatures : vector<Creature*>
  + get_creature(size_t x, size_t y) -> Creature*
  + get_tile(size_t x, size_t y) -> const Tile*
  + get_interactable(size_t x, size_t y) -> Interactable*
}

class Tile {
}

class Interactable {
}

class Creature_AI {
}

class Simple_AI {
}

class Ground_melee_AI {
}

class Ground_ranged_AI {
}

class Flying_melee_AI {
}

class Flying_ranged_AI {
}

note "Storing a behaviour type reference will allow cretures to have different behaviours e.g. depending on creature type and modifiers, etc.\n\nWould like to avoid the complexity caused by indirection if possible."
note "Level_master is responsible for handling the logic of gameplay interactions between level objects e.g. creatures, interactibles, etc.\n\nLevel_master serves to separate concerns between gameplay interaction logic and tile data handling e.g. map generation, bounds checks etc.\n\nThat said, having \"friend\" classes is often an indication of bad design, so this is likely not the final solution.\nWill think some more on alternative solutions."

Creature --|> Creature_AI : indirect ref.
Creature_AI <|-- Simple_AI
Creature_AI <|-- Ground_melee_AI
Creature_AI <|-- Ground_ranged_AI
Creature_AI <|-- Flying_melee_AI
Creature_AI <|-- Flying_ranged_AI

Creature --* Level_map
Level_master --|> Level_map : friend to
Level_master -- Creature

@enduml
